<!-- Tutorial Section -->
<section id="tutorial">
<div class="container">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-12 text-center">
      <h2 class="section-heading">Tutorial</h2>
      <h3 class="section-subheading text-muted">How to create your own 'Blender AR Nano Film' using Blender and WebAR?</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-4 col-sm-6 tutorial-item">
      <a href="#tutorialModal1" class="tutorial-link" data-toggle="modal">
        <div class="tutorial-hover">
          <div class="tutorial-hover-content">
            <i class="fa fa-plus fa-3x"></i>
          </div>
        </div>
        <img src="img/tutorial/01-thumbnail.jpg" class="img-responsive" alt="">
      </a>
      <div class="tutorial-caption">
        <h4>Step 1: Create your 3D model and animation in Blender</h4>
        <p class="text-muted">You can use any of the features and tools that Blender offers, such as rigging, sculpting, texturing, lighting, etc. You can also use any of the assets and add-ons that Blender provides, such as characters, environments, materials, etc.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-4 col-sm-6 tutorial-item">
      <a href="#tutorialModal2" class="tutorial-link" data-toggle="modal">
        <div class="tutorial-hover">
          <div class="tutorial-hover-content">
            <i class="fa fa-plus fa-3x"></i>
          </div>
        </div>
        <img src="img/tutorial/02-thumbnail.jpg" class="img-responsive" alt="">
      </a>
      <div class="tutorial-caption">
        <h4>Step 2: Export your 3D model and animation to glTF</h4>
        <p class="text-muted">You can use the built-in glTF exporter in Blender, or you can use a plugin like this one: https://github.com/KhronosGroup/glTF-Blender-IO. You have to adjust the export parameters, reduce the file size and solve any possible issues.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-4 col-sm-6 tutorial-item">
      <a href="#tutorialModal3" class="tutorial-link" data-toggle="modal">
        <div class="tutorial-hover">
          <div class="tutorial-hover-content">
            <i class="fa fa-plus fa-3x"></i>
          </div>
        </div>
        <img src="img/tutorial/03-thumbnail.jpg" class="img-responsive" alt="">
      </a>
      <div class="tutorial-caption">
        <h4>Step 3: Create your WebAR scene using MindAR and three.js</h4>
        <p class="text-muted">You have to load your glTF file, create a light and a camera, and add some interactivity and effects. You can use the examples and the documentation that MindAR and three.js provide, or you can use some of the code that I have created for you.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-4 col-sm-6 tutorial-item">
      <a href="#tutorialModal4" class="tutorial-link" data-toggle="modal">
        <div class="tutorial-hover">
          <div class="tutorial-hover-content">
            <i class="fa fa-plus fa-3x"></i>
          </div>
        </div>
        <img src="img/tutorial/04-thumbnail.jpg" class="img-responsive" alt="">
      </a>
      <div class="tutorial-caption">
        <h4>Step 4: Deploy your WebAR project on GitHub</h4>
        <p class="text-muted">You have to create a repository, upload your files, and enable the GitHub Pages feature. You can use the instructions and the help that GitHub offers, or you can follow this tutorial: https://pages.github.com/. You will get a URL that you can use to access your WebAR project from any device.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

