        <div class="col-lg-8 col-lg-offset-2">
          <div class="modal-body">
            <!-- Tutorial Details Go Here -->
            <h2>Step 2: Export your 3D model and animation to glTF</h2>
            <p class="item-intro text-muted">You can use the built-in glTF exporter in Blender, or you can use a plugin like this one: https://github.com/KhronosGroup/glTF-Blender-IO. You have to adjust the export parameters, reduce the file size and solve any possible issues.</p>
            <img class="img-responsive img-centered" src="img/tutorial/02-full.jpg" alt="">
            <p>In this step, you will export your 3D model and animation to glTF, the standard format for Augmented Reality on the Web. You can follow these substeps:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Select your 3D object and go to File > Export > glTF 2.0.</li>
              <li>Choose a name and a location for your glTF file.</li>
              <li>Choose the export options that suit your needs, such as the format (binary or JSON), the compression, the animation, etc.</li>
              <li>Click on Export glTF and wait for the process to finish.</li>
              <li>Check your glTF file for any errors or warnings, and fix them if necessary.</li>
              <li>Reduce the file size of your glTF file if it is too large, using tools like this one: https://github.com/zeux/meshoptimizer</li>
            </ul>
            <p>You can find more information and tips about glTF here: https://docs.blender.org/manual/en/latest/addons/import_export/scene_gltf2.html</p>
            <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" data-dismiss="modal"><i class="fa fa-times"></i> Close Step</button>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Tutorial Modal 3 -->
<div class="tutorial-modal modal fade" id="tutorialModal3" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-hidden="true">
  <div class="modal-content">
    <div class="close-modal" data-dismiss="modal">
      <div class="lr">
