      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-lg-8 col-lg-offset-2">
          <div class="modal-body">
            <!-- Tutorial Details Go Here -->
            <h2>Step 3: Create your WebAR scene using MindAR and three.js</h2>
            <p class="item-intro text-muted">You have to load your glTF file, create a light and a camera, and add some interactivity and effects. You can use the examples and the documentation that MindAR and three.js provide, or you can use some of the code that I have created for you.</p>
            <img class="img-responsive img-centered" src="img/tutorial/03-full.jpg" alt="">
            <p>In this step, you will create your WebAR scene using MindAR and three.js, two free and open source libraries for Augmented Reality on the Web. You can follow these substeps:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Create an HTML file and a JavaScript file for your WebAR project.</li>
              <li>Include the scripts of MindAR and three.js in your HTML file, using the links or the files that they provide.</li>
              <li>Create a scene, a renderer, and a camera in your JavaScript file, using the three.js API.</li>
              <li>Create a light and add it to your scene, using the three.js API.</li>
              <li>Create a loader and load your glTF file, using the three.js API.</li>
              <li>Create a controller and add some interactivity to your scene, using the three.js API.</li>
              <li>Create an arController and add some effects to your scene, using the MindAR API.</li>
              <li>Create a loop and update your scene, using the three.js API and the MindAR API.</li>

<li>Test your WebAR project on your browser and on your cell phone, using the URL or the QR code that GitHub provides.</li>
</ul>
<p>You can find more information and examples about MindAR and three.js here: https://github.com/hiukim/mind-ar-js and https://threejs.org/</p>
<button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" data-dismiss="modal"><i class="fa fa-times"></i> Close Step</button>
