<div class="modal-body">
<!-- Tutorial Details Go Here -->
<h2>Step 4: Deploy your WebAR project on GitHub</h2>
<p class="item-intro text-muted">You have to create a repository, upload your files, and enable the GitHub Pages feature. You can use the instructions and the help that GitHub offers, or you can follow this tutorial: https://pages.github.com/. You will get a URL that you can use to access your WebAR project from any device.</p>
<img class="img-responsive img-centered" src="img/tutorial/04-full.jpg" alt="">
<p>In this step, you will deploy your WebAR project on GitHub, a free and popular platform for hosting and sharing code. You can follow these substeps:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Create an account on GitHub, if you don't have one already.</li>
  <li>Create a new repository on GitHub, with the name of your WebAR project.</li>
  <li>Upload your HTML file, your JavaScript file, your glTF file, and any other files that your WebAR project needs.</li>
  <li>Go to the settings of your repository and enable the GitHub Pages feature, using the main branch as the source.</li>
  <li>Wait for a few minutes until GitHub Pages generates and publishes your WebAR project.</li>
  <li>Copy the URL that GitHub Pages provides and use it to access your WebAR project from any device.</li>
  <li>Optionally, you can create a QR code from your URL and use it to scan it with your cell phone.</li>
</ul>
<p>You can find more information and help about GitHub and GitHub Pages here: https://github.com/ and https://pages.github.com/</p>
<button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" data-dismiss="modal"><i class="fa fa-times"></i> Close Step</button>
